{{complex}}
'''Yamato no Iotari''' was [[Nobility|an aristocrat]] from [[Asuka period|the Asuka period]] to [[Nara period|the Nara period]] . His {{ill|10=ja|11=ŃéźŃâÉŃâŹ|Kabane|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was {{ill|10=ja|11=ň┐îň»Ş|Ikisui|qq=draft|qq=draft}} . His {{ill|Kan'i s┼Źt┼Ź system|lt=official Rank|ja|ň«śńŻŹšŤŞňŻôňłÂ|simple|User:Immanuelle/Kan'i s┼Źt┼Ź system|en:draft|8=en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank|ja|ňżôń║öńŻŹ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and his job was {{ill|10=ja|11=f|Ministry_of_Justice_(pre-modern_Japan)|en|lt=Junior Assistant Minister of Justice|qq=draft|qq=draft}} .

He served under {{ill|Emperor Monmu|en}}, [[Empress Gemmei]], [[Empress Gensh┼Ź]], and {{ill|Emperor Sh┼Źmu|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Origin ==
The [[Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Yamato clan]] was a clan of {{ill|Kunitsukami|en}}. <ref>[[ňĄ¬šö░ń║«]]ŃÇÄňžôŠ░Ćň«Âš│╗ňĄžŔż×ňůŞŃÇĆ[[ŔžĺňĚŁŠŤŞň║Ś]]ŃÇü1963rd year </ref> The clan's ancestor was {{ill|Saonetsuhiko|simple|User:Immanuelle/Saonetsuhiko|fr|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who was a distinguished figure during {{ill|Jimmu%27s Eastern Expedition|en}} . <ref>ŃÇÄ[[Nihon Shoki]]ŃÇĆšą×ŠşŽŠ«ÁŃÇéŃÇÄ[[Šľ░Šĺ░ňžôŠ░ĆÚî▓]]ŃÇĆňĄžňĺîšą×ňłąŃüžŃü»ŃÇîšą×ščąŠ┤ąňŻŽňĹŻŃÇŹŃüĘŃüÖŃéőŃÇé</ref>
{{Short description|Japanese noble family|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
Their [[Ujigami]] or clan god is [[Yamato Okunitama]] of [[┼îyamato Shrine]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=International Symposium "Perspectives on Japanese history and literature from ancient historical records"|url=https://www.waseda.jp/inst/sgu/news-en/2019/04/12/5171|access-date=2023-05-04|website=Top Global University Project: Waseda Goes Global|language=en}}</ref> Some scholars interpret the ''kami'' as being a variant or epithet of [[┼îmononushi]] who has much more widespread worship.<ref name="Ellwood-19902">{{Cite journal|last=Ellwood|first=Robert S.|date=1990|title=The Sujin Religious Revolution|journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies|volume=17|issue=2/3|pages=199ÔÇô217|doi=10.18874/jjrs.17.2-3.1990.199-217|issn=0304-1042|jstor=30234018|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Q81DQAAQBAJ|title=Shinto: A History|last=Hardacre|first=Helen|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-062171-1|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|22}} There is a complex myth about the origins of modern worship of [[Yamato Okunitama]] during the reign of [[Emperor Sujin]].<ref name="D-20122">{{Cite web|last=D|first=John|date=2012-11-10|title=Teeuwen on Shinto|url=https://www.greenshinto.com/2012/11/10/teeuwen-on-shinto/|access-date=2023-05-04|website=Green Shinto|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name="japanpolicy2">https://www.japanpolicyforum.jp/pdf/2016/no35/DJweb_35_cul_02.pdf</ref><ref name="freidok2">https://freidok.uni-freiburg.de/fedora/objects/freidok:4635/datastreams/FILE1/content</ref><ref name="Nihongi2">{{Citation|title=Book V|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Nihongi:_Chronicles_of_Japan_from_the_Earliest_Times_to_A.D._697/Book_V|work=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 1|access-date=2023-05-04}}</ref>


[[File:Hibara-jinja,_torii_closeup.jpg|thumb|240x240px|Hibara Shrine, at the foot of [[Mount Miwa]] in [[Sakurai, Nara]], identified as the place where the Yata-no-Kagami and the Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi were first enshrined after their removal from the imperial palace.]]
During {{ill|Jimmu%27s Eastern Expedition|en}} {{ill|Saonetsuhiko|ja|ŠĄÄŠá╣Š┤ąňŻŽ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was given the position of governor of [[Yamato Province]] by [[Emperor Jimmu]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Friday: Kojiki (ŃÇîń╣×ÚúčŃÇŹŃüžŃü»Ńü¬ŃüĆŃÇÄňĆĄń║őŔĘśŃÇĆŃüžŃüÖŃâĘ´╝ü´╝ü) #26|url=https://japaneseexperts.net/972/|access-date=2023-05-04|website=Japanese Experts Net|language=en-US}}</ref> And Saonetsuhiko became their ancestor.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2023-10-26|title=Saonetsuhiko {{!}} ňťőňşŞÚÖóňĄžňşŞŃâçŃéŞŃé┐ŃâźŃâčŃâąŃâ╝ŃéŞŃéóŃâá|url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9159|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231026183115/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9159|archive-date=2023-10-26|access-date=2023-12-04}}</ref>

After the divination, {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|ňŞéšú»ÚĽĚň░żňŞé|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a descendant of {{ill|Saonetsuhiko|ja|ŠĄÄŠá╣Š┤ąňŻŽ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} would conduct the rites pertaining to Okunitama, replacing the emaciated Nunaki-iri-hime.<ref name="Ellwood-19902" /> {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|ňŞéšú»ÚĽĚň░żňŞé|qq=draft|qq=draft}} would be the ancestor of the Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Page:Nihongi by Aston.djvu/208|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Nihongi_by_Aston.djvu/208|access-date=2023-10-24|website=en.wikisource.org|language=en}}</ref>


== Biography ==
In the first year of the reign of {{ill|Emperor Monmu|en}} ( 697 ), he traveled overland to [[Tsukushi Province]] as an envoy to welcome {{ill|10=ja|11=Šľ░šżůńŻ┐|the Silla envoys|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (his Rank at the time was Shin Daiichi). [[710|In 710]], he was promoted from [[Wad┼Ź (era)|Junior]] Sixth Rank to Junior Fifth Rank . In 714, he became {{ill|10=ja|11=Š░ĆÚĽĚŔÇů|the head of the clan|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and was in charge of religious services. In the 7th year [[Y┼Źr┼Ź|of the Yoro era]] ( 723 ), Kii, a man from {{ill|Sakyo|en}}, presented a white turtle, which was deemed an auspicious omen, and as the [[kuni no miyatsuko]] (Owa kuni no miyatsuko) of the country that had brought the turtle, he was bestowed with 10 pieces of silk, 100 pieces of [[hemp]], and 20 pieces [[Textile|of cloth]] .

In the third year [[Jinki (era)|of the Jinki]] era ( 726 ), he was promoted to the Rank of Junior Fifth Rank. In 727, at a banquet celebrating the birth of {{ill|Emperor Sh┼Źmu|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 's son, {{ill|10=ja|11=ňč║šÄő|Prince Motoi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, anyone of fifth {{ill|List of Japanese court Ranks, positions and hereditary titles|en|lt=Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft}} or higher was given [[hemp]], and especially the eldest son of a prominent family of fifth Rank or higher was given an additional ten bolts of silk. However, Gohyakutaku was specially added to this list along with {{ill|10=ja|11=Ŕ¬┐ŠĚíŠÁĚ|Chotankai|qq=draft|qq=draft}} because of his advanced age.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Yu|first=A. C.|title=Tsuki no Omi - Japanese Wiki Corpus|url=https://www.japanesewiki.com/person/TSUKI%20no%20Omi.html|access-date=2024-04-09|website=www.japanesewiki.com}}</ref>

Year of death unknown. His final official Rank was Junior Fifth Rank and Junior Assistant Minister of Justice. <ref>ŃÇÄ[[šÂÜŠŚąŠťČš┤Ç]]ŃÇĆ[[šą×ŔşĚŠÖ»ÚŤ▓]]3rd year 10Šťł29ŠŚąŠŁí</ref>

== Family tree ==
Many clans may be descendants of Furutama no Mikoto. This includes the {{ill|Owari clan|ja|ň░żň╝ÁŠ░Ć|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and [[Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko]]. This is a subject of debate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422190938/http://wwr2.ucom.ne.jp/hetoyc15/keihu/amabe/amabe-k2.htm|access-date=2023-12-13|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>
